Moore's Ford Bridge massacre: activists remember racist lynching
The 1948 Ford Mercury passed by the onlookers of Monroe, Georgia, and peered toward Moore's Ford Bridge.
But before the car with four black passengers and a white driver could reach the bridge, a group of armed whites barricaded its way.
The leader of the group - a middle-aged man in a striped suit - pulled out a cigarette and looked at the windshield.
The passengers inside were trembling with fear.
"We want that Roger!" shouted the man.
Bring him to me!
Silence is broken by the roar of a young black man being pulled from the passenger seat.
This scene is fortunately a mere reconstruction of the events that occurred on July 22.
But when one of the men throws a rope over Roger's neck, the audience sighs with excitement.
Since 2005, a group of activists have returned to Moore's Ford Bridge to reconstruct the fateful night in 1946 when two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and Mae Murra Dorsey - were killed by members of the Ku Klux Klan.
No one's been tried for murder yet.
"It's amazing that in all these years not a single person has been arrested - even though we still see them in our community; even though we know their identities", said Tyrone Brooks, who is helping to re-organize the event.
It's a stain on our history and a burden on our souls.
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia state congressman and a lifelong civil rights activist.
In his eyes, the reenactment of the event is a dramatic call to action, reminding the Monroe community every year that justice has not been done enough.
"We demand prosecution and closure of the case, we want peace of mind and reconciliation, but justice first", Brooks said.
Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot begin.
A coroner covers one of the bodies of lynch victims at Moore's Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, up to 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were expected to participate in the lynching.
But no one has been prosecuted yet.
Although the suspects remain at large for decades, civil rights advocates claim that both reasons for the lynchings - political and sexual - were known to all the townspeople.
In April 1946, the Supreme Court granted black citizens of Georgia the right to vote in elections scheduled for the summer.
And just in time for the summer election, the FBI says a black farmer, Roger Malcolm, was stabbed in a brawl by a white landowner, Barnett Hester, allegedly over his wife.
According to Brooks, there was a townwide rumor that Hester had been having intercourse with Malcolm's wife Dorothy and had brought her into a different state.
According to the FBI's statement, on July 25, 1946, then-prominent white landowner, Loy Harrison, posted a $600 bail for Malcolm.
He was accompanied to prison by Dorothy and cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
On their way back from prison, just before entering the Moore's Ford Bridge, they were surrounded by a group of suspects.
As it turns out, the murders were planned and orchestrated by Harrison, and conducted by the FBI.
It is also clear that there was a collusion between state and local law enforcement who not only participated in the lynching, but also disposed of evidence and concealed the identities of witnesses.
Brooks was a little more concise on the whole thing.
"It was a massacre for the right to vote", he said.
The murders had a clear message for all black people in the area: "This is what happens if you register and vote".
The annual reenactment of the Moore's Ford Bridge event has been organized for nearly a decade by Cassandra Greene.
Her performance is graphic, engaging and apt, showing the deep-seated racism that many would like to see extinct in modern America.
Watching this reconstruction is not easy, and it's even harder to look away, but Greene says it makes sense.
"Nobody wants to talk about lynching because we have to face the uncomfortable feelings that lurk inside each of us", Greene said.
But we can't have a relationship unless you listen to what I've been through.
The main rehearsals for this year's production began in June, and on the very first day, about 30 actors - a dozen white, the rest black - swarmed into the room, where Greene introduced them to a very carefully planned performance.
Wade Marbaugh is acting as assistant director.
He's played the leader of the Kuklux Klan for many years, but he says the role is exhausting.
"I feel bad about it because it goes against who I am", Marbaugh said.
I think it's very important to remember this part of history regularly because we never want to go back to that time.
Actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play the roles of Roger Malcolm, also Barnett Hester, rehearse their roles.
The show opens with a fight - Malcolm argues with Hester and blames him for sleeping with his wife.
Get off my property!
There's no such thing as rascón.
There's a fight going on.
At that moment, everyone (at least every black actor) bursts out laughing.
Greene's the one who laughs the most.
"What happened?" he asks Rascón.
He's confused.
Was I too rude?
"No", Greene says cheerfully.
I just don't think white people used to say "n-r" in that tone.
That's right, one of the black actors is going to pop.
You have to put more emphasis on the R.
The energy in the room is suddenly better; the hostility is replaced by a sense of closeness.
Everyone wants the show to be authentic, just to be done for enough four victims of the massacre.
The actors repeat the scene.
Rascona's emphasis this time is on the correct pronunciation of the N word.
No one laughs anymore.
The show ends violently and quickly.
The roar, the gunshots... and the silence.
A woman dressed in black stands over the bodies of the actors and sings Billie Holiday's mournful song "Strange Fruit".
Every word, there's a sadness in the room.
Against this backdrop, a dozen or so onlookers wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
There are practically equal numbers of blacks and whites in the audience.
One couple came all the way from Ithaca, New York, and many onlookers are from the surrounding area.
Each of them endures the local humidity for nearly eight hours, and Brooks leads them in droves to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Up until this point, the murders could be viewed from a distance, but now, standing in the same place where the lynchings took place, the atmosphere is eerie.
With the last words of the song, Greene calls the crowd to inspect the bodies.
Children kneel at the heads of their victims, watch for fake blood and still bodies, and whisper in their ears.
They're not dead, they're a little boy.
A few minutes go by and Greene thanks the audience.
The actors clean the rope and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh, the man in the suit who played the leader of the Kuklux Klan.
Nick Rascona hugs his two fellow actors and cries in their arms; eventually, he is overcome with emotion.
"It's all right", one of the women whispers.
