Recent results of age-limit tests in Sweden
Recent results of tests on asylum seekers in Sweden who were subjected to a new age-assessing method show that over 80 percent of those interviewed were over 18, but not everyone believes their accuracy.
The Swedish Forensic Medical Agency (Råttsmedicinalverket) started conducting new tests earlier this year.
The aim of the method is to assess applicants more accurately in the evaluation of asylum applications. e measure was taken after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticised for failing to correctly age some refugees who lied about their age.
To date, the Swedish Migration Agency has referred 6,880 cases for investigation and the Forensic Medical Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests carried out from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
80 percent (2002) were assessed as over 18 years of age, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medical Agency judged that the respondent was possibly over 18 years of age.
In a further 423 cases it was decided that the respondent was under 18 years of age.
The tests shall only be accessed if the age of the respondent is disputed.
According to Johan Gransson of the Forensic Medical Agency, the results are consistent with the previous month.
Compared to last month, the statistics are holding in busy lanes and the numbers are very similar, he told The Local.
The higher number of applicants whose age was estimated to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers lie about their age.
In May, the agency published results of 581 tests and said that 442 cases had been found to be 18 years of age or older.
Svenska Dagbladet investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases the respondent said that he would be 18 this year.
Criticism has also been directed at the medical method of ageing, which involves X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of the knee joints, which are then evaluated by dentists and radiologists.
