And Becoming Resemblance: an artist creates portraits using DNA from Chelsea Manning
In the center of one room at the Friedman Gallery in New York City, there are several faces of different shades of skin - white, black, and brown - hanging from the ceiling on wires, each one as if out of the eye of the other.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from oral swabs and hair sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth, where the former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for illegally leaking classified cables to WikiLeaks.
The new exhibit, which opened on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It's the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her expertise in technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a transgender and pioneering dissident whose sentence was commuted by Obama three days before she left office as president of the United States.
By algorithmically analyzing Manning's DNA and using 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a sharp, if not intellectual, commentary on the susceptibility of DNA - as well as the many ways in which DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of those interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, born Bradley Edward Manning, has spoken openly about being a woman since she was a young girl, and was convicted in 2013 on 20 counts, including six counts of espionage, computer fraud and theft.
All of her photographs were seized by prison staff, with only one black and white photograph leaked to the public, a lower quality photograph showing Manning, visibly distraught, sitting in the driver's seat in the platinum blonde wig she's now associated with.
In 2015, there was still a positive response to Dewey-Hagborg's 2012 project Stranger Visions.
In this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create a picture of the possible shapes of these people.
And just about this time, she received an email from Paper Magazine.
"They were planning to interview Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to add a portrait to the article", Dewey-Hagborg explained at the opening of the new exhibition.
But visitors and photography were not allowed, so they approached Chelsea and asked if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends over the course of two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea was pardoned and allowed to attend the exhibition in person.
President Obama did, in fact, ask for Manning's release a few days after the comic was published, which was a welcome change after several excruciating years in a military prison in Kansas.
Interestingly, the exhibition comes at a time when Donald Trump is waging war on people who seek to leak government information and transgender soldiers, while trying to find new ways to tweet hate speech in areas he is supposed to be supporting.
In response to a question about this particular timing, Dewey-Hagborg stated that "everything happens for a reason".
Under the artist's statement on one of the gallery walls, Manning calls with her huge signature (the  in her last name is a heart) for an end to self-inflicted factionalism based on gender, race, sexuality and culture.
On the opposite side are the sequences of her mitochondrial DNA -- the centipede letters C, G and A, written in pencil.
By listing 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist's sophisticated scientific dictionary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we are all.
"I hope people will learn that our genome doesn't matter who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and can be interpreted in a different way", said Dewey-Hagborg.
DNA tells many different stories, and this is 30 of them.
The last copy of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is a single page of the aforementioned graphic novel.
It shows Manning emerging in a King Kong fashion from the United States Disciplinary Barracks with a megaphone in her hand.
"Once they stop you from speaking, they win", it says.
Never be silenced.
"It's a direct transcript of one of the letters", said the Philadelphia artist.
I get goose bumps when I think about it.
Manning has not yet visited the exhibition in person, as predicted in the comic book, but when she does, she will be welcomed into the center of the room with her masks, her own genome images, lined up like a mob of Protestants.
That was also the purpose of the exhibition, including a nearly five-foot-tall statue of Manning, which is marked with pencil with her genetic haplogroups.
"In the past, they were on the walls, but this time I wanted to make them feel like a crowd", Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
I wanted to create the impression of a mass movement taking the form of Chelsea and liberating her.
