Startups that will help your company avoid another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure employee satisfaction at her e-commerce startup, but she couldn't find a survey that matched her.
The answers were often inaccurate, unhelpful, or even misleading.
And despite her promise of anonymity, some employees expressed their distrust of the entire process.
"I was looking for consistency and objectivity", says Errett, owner of Madison Reed, a San Francisco-based e-commerce hair care company that employs 75 people.
So she asked for outside help.
New HR startups are constantly emerging in the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By building and licensing software with the specific intent of measuring employee engagement, startups allow companies to conduct quick voting, target specific teams and demographics, offer complete employee anonymity and a complaint hotline, and in some cases also allow whistleblowers to bypass superiors and contact the CEO directly.
"There are tools on the market like Strava and Fitbit that track your health, but where's Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said that Glint has helped her to become more aware of what her employees think and feel in three years.
In addition to quick surveys and team-specific voting, Glint offers a company temperature map and a concise overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of low-rated managers - allowing users to work on a fix.
Companies are starting to realize the need to take care of the workplace culture - in case they become another Uber - which is being mired in scandal after a former employee posted a blog post describing the workplace and harassment of employees who dare to speak out.
For startups like Glint, the demand for culture surveys is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the Let's Talk Payments website, which focuses on technical and financial advances, the global control, regulation and compliance industry could be worth more than $118.8 billion by 2020.
Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small surge in interest and activity earlier this year, just before the Uber scandals.
Convergent's nearly 600 clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
He recently took Uber under his wing.
Similar to Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable flash surveys, collect sensitive information in real time and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If the Director-General is involved, complaints shall be sent directly to the Management Board.
"The court of public opinion has regulators on its side", said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
If a company is convicted of mistreatment or unethical behavior - and if regulators do not act - it can face costly consequences from customer boycotts, employee exhaustion or lawsuits, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant chain, which employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to raise awareness among employees of company policies and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate management.
In the past, if an employee wanted to report any problem, he had to look up the company's phone number or e-mail address, formally file a complaint, and hope for a successful solution.
Often, it was a daunting and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, Ruby Tuesday's general counsel, who said there was no reliable way to track employee complaints before.
Now, when companies use Convercent, they can quickly detect and resolve problems that have never before been addressed by managers sitting in offices miles away from actual complaint resolution - such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
"It's getting closer to a holistic, holistic view of the employee experience", said Vitrano, who heads Ruby Tuesday's risk management group.
We also protect shareholders from employee lawsuits.
Companies stopped taking ethics, values and employee participation lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed after Enron's collapse over the abuse of employee ethics rights, Quinlan said.
But it wasn't until social media brought the whole thing to light that companies started to realize that in the online world, they can't just hide their skeletons in a closet.
"Before people started using technology to track ethics, they relied on faith", added Quinlan.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service for which the companies pay a regular fee.
It's a business model and an opportunity that's been embraced by the bold venture capitalists who backed both startups.
Convercent raised $10 million in its February campaign from companies like Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, and ultimately took in $47 million in equity.
Glint raised $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners and raised $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, cultures and venture capital.
A growing body of research clearly confirms that today's employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects aren't the main advantages.
Employees want to feel accepted and valued and that they are giving their time to a company that strives for a positive mission.
When people are happy in their jobs, feel their voices are heard, and feel their work is rewarding, they contribute to the success of the company, said Nina McQueen, VP of Global Benefits and Perks at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors make money when companies thrive, and companies thrive when their employees are happy.
And when an analytical tool comes on the market to ensure employee engagement and commitment to the company, it's no wonder there are a lot of investors who will support this effort.
According to experts in work culture, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But data alone is useless unless society takes the necessary steps.
The reality is that once a company asks for feedback from its employees, big changes can happen.
And if change is not made quickly - or at worst not at all - it can cause frustration and disinterest among employees.
"Once you ask for 4,000 opinions, you have to be prepared for 4,000 conversations", said Russell Raath, director of consultancy at Kotter International, who has seen many companies rely too much on data alone.
Because once you don't get things done, the employees start asking themselves, "Did they even hear me?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, why should I care?'"
Madison Reed, which now conducts regular monthly employee surveys, can solve the problem in a day with Glinto, Errett said.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated with the slow decision-making and quality of communication, Errett was able to reorganise several teams within the company and start communication training to successfully solve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining a very important perspective on its employees and hopes to achieve high employment in the long term in a sector that is known for frequent layoffs.
If you do not strive to create a transparent work environment, employees will not trust you, added Vitrano.
And once you start losing employees, you're going to lose customers.
And with the flow of customers, the whole company goes bankrupt.
