He drank whiskey and wrote at night.
Scotney's private history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust did not gain access to the documents until 2006 after the death of the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived on the scene ten years later, the staff were just beginning to penetrate the archives, which Rhodes described as the aristocrats of many centuries waving their hands with the words, "Take it to the attic".
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps of property: "You may think a land dispute is boring", said Rhodes, "but I came across one case where two families were fighting over a birch.
Stop it people!
Some of the stories in the book use the castle as a springboard and delve deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves a newly built castle to join the English Rebellion of 1381.
