The English rebellion actually started in this area, and I thought the rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe they're connected after all.
Other stories are firmly linked to the castle's history - for example The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell who allegedly faked his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (which was not discovered until years after the coffin was discovered).
Rhodes' favorite family is the Darrells: "I was interested in the male generation - men were always in debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Different generations of the Darrells have dealt with this by marrying rich or old ladies - I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to screw with heirs.
With his stay at the castle over, Rhodes is looking for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week stint in the Finnish wilderness, where he was inspired to write his next book about Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that has been absorbed by nature.
