Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may alleviate symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
Red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare for your digestive system.
A new study, however, suggests the opposite: A diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
A chronic disease that affects up to 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, it causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Although patients are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan found in protein helps to build immune cells that support intestinal resistance.
Dr. Marco Colonna, the study's leader, explained that immune cells protect the intestines and help to break down harmful microbes in food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the scales are tilted to the side of inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
In the study, the researchers found the presence of immune cells that promote the body's tolerance to a particular bacterium in the stomach of mice.
This bacterium requires tryptophan, one of the building blocks of proteins, to make cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We found a link between a type of bacteria called Lactobacillus reuteri, which is a normal part of the gut microbiome, and the development of cells that promote tolerance in the body.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had.
He also suggested that if the same was shown to be true in humans, then the combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet would help to develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory gut environment.
As part of a study of a type of immune cell that promotes body tolerance, postgraduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas found that one group of test mice had these cells, while another group of the same mice raised separately lacked them.
She reasoned that one group of mice had a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The gut of the mice was tested using DNA sequencing, and the researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the other group of mice lacked.
Mice that were raised in a sterile environment and lacked the gut microbiome -- they didn't develop these kinds of immune cells -- were given L. reuteri, and they developed immune cells.
To understand how the bacteria affect the immune system, researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid and then transferred a small amount of the liquid - without the bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
The immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removal of the active substance from the liquid, it was found to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indole-3-octate acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of these cells increased by 50 percent, and when they halved the tryptophan doses, the number of cells dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us store L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: "Each of us should probably strive to develop these cells, because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially high tryptophan levels in the presence of L. reuteri bacteria may increase the cell population.
