Thirty-three-year-old Steven Northam has had a tiny chip implanted between his thumb and forefinger and is now offering the same service through his company BioTeq to companies and individuals who want to use technology to simplify their lives.
The implantation procedure and adherence to treatment procedures is supervised by Dr Geoff Watson, an anaesthetist at the Royal Hampshire County Hospital in Winchester.
The technology works on the same principle as microchips implanted in dogs and cats, and the whole procedure takes 30 seconds.
Northam's company also offers a service to replace microchip-compatible car and door locks at a cost of £300 each.
A married father of one has had technology integrated into his home and his BMW Z4 car, which starts with a simple wave of his hand.
The White House prop cost the taxpayers thousands of dollars .
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to the South Lawn for a celebration of American manufacturing last month came at a cost of $24,000, according to Navy records published by TIME magazine.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One in the presence of the President on board, was the highlight of a July 17 White House program that was a demonstration of American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials were watching a showcase of products from all 50 states.
A helicopter from Connecticut was displayed alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a fork lift from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, requesting the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn in an "emergency" incident, according to records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant event", wrote the commander of HMX-1 in an email to his superior, the deputy naval aviation commander, the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 a.m. for the parade, which is scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m. and remain in place until the entire site is fully cleared, which was scheduled to take place between 6:00 and 9:00 p.m.
The e-mail also said that if there was a delay in the departure from the White House, a flight crew would be sent back for a return flight due to work hours regulations.
The original crew remained on the scene that evening with a helicopter and a security team.
The recordings - obtained by TIME - did not indicate whether a second crew was eventually sent.
The Hatch Act prohibits government officials from using government property for political purposes.
The records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating possible violations of this regulation.
"We were wondering if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and were assured that everything was in order", the commander wrote.
"Sounds like you're being blocked", the deputy commander wrote.
This "Made in America" parade was designated by the White House as an official event and therefore would not be covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
In his speech, the president was promoting health care reform that was going through the Senate and talking about trying to rein in government regulation.
The use of aerial vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when they travel.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered the check in February after a presidential jet flew in the background at his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida.
"The White House is pleased with the 'Made in America' showcase, which showcases products from all 50 states made by Americans using American materials", said Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
The crews of the HMX-1 helicopter often practice landing in the Washington area and on the South Lawn and rehearse possible arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump was attending the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, the HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
The Made in America show was part of the crew's ongoing training, the official said.
The helicopter unit flew on the same day on a non-presidential support mission for another 11 hours.
The White House has stated that no other props were paid for with taxpayer money.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was not involved in any way in the negotiations to display the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights and the exact costs associated with the parade are difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly rate for fiscal year 2017, the DoD's reimbursement for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
Unit logs show a 30-minute flight from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below that amount.
"To cite taxpayers' costs on the basis of estimates for reimbursement is very misleading", Walters said of the whole case.
These estimates include staff, maintenance and many other hidden costs which are included in the annual cost.
The Commission notes that the costs of the measures are not directly linked to the costs of the military.
The then White House press secretary Sean Spicer advocated using a helicopter for the purpose of the parade.
"The idea of the show this week is to showcase products made in the U.S"., Spicer said.
I'm aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut take great pride in the fact that they contribute to the defense of our state and that they provide employment for hundreds, if not thousands of people.
I think, like most Americans, we are proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that countless American citizens are involved in building.
This fact is worth recalling.
It's unclear if Trump was on his patrol on the South Lawn to see if the helicopter was involved, but we can only say with certainty that he was behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back at the White House, Trump addressed a Sikorsky representative and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorski very well", said the President, "I own three of them".
