According to the UN, Afghan democracy relies on women in politics.
Elections can only be credible if all members of society, including women, participate, the UN representative in Afghanistan said on Wednesday.
Nicholas Haysom, head of the UN Assistance Mission, said that hundreds of women are running for local councils, three women are running for vice president, and more than 30 percent of newly registered voters are women.
The role of women cannot be overlooked,he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can only be fully representative and credible if women are involved, as well as in all related processes related to elections.
Local and presidential elections are due to be held in Afghanistan on April 5.
The Taliban have issued several threats against the electoral process, which is moving international combat activity into the second round.
In this year's election, for the first time ever, a democratically elected government is handing over power to a peaceful successor.
Haysom said that a strong role for women would strengthen Afghanistan's democracy.
The Independent Electoral Commission of Afghanistan said that 1.2 million of the 3.6 million registered voters are women.
