Get to know the plant with one click.
The new free application Pl@ntNet will help both students of herbal medicine and ordinary plant lovers.
If they're wondering what plant they just came across on the walk, this app will tell them.
All they have to do is take a picture of the plant, and the app will recognize the species.
The new app, which is available for both iOS and Android, was unveiled on Tuesday by representatives of the CEEV Centre for Ethical and Environmental Education in Bratislava's Mountain Park as part of the project Secret Life of the City.
Students from 50 Czech and Slovak schools also took part in the project, taking pictures with their teachers and adding plants from their surroundings to the application's database.
A newly created French app is free to download on the Secret Life of the City website.
The main goal of the French developers was to get as many people as possible to contribute their images to the app, thus increasing the number of plants that the app can recognize.
"Children who hold a tablet or mobile phone in their hands can now go into the forest", said Ivana Poláčková, the project coordinator.
Based on a high-quality photo of a flower, leaf or fruit, the app can identify the name of the plant within seconds and then assign it to the photo in both Czech and Slovak.
The French have allowed us to translate the app into Slovak and Czech for the project Secret Life of the City.
Therefore, users are welcome to contribute a photo of a plant not yet present in the database after creating an account in the application.
"The French will evaluate whether it is useful and then add it to the database", Poláčková informed.
GMB's concerns about its investment in McVitie's factory in Glasgow
The unions are demanding assurances from the managers of McVitie's biscuit maker about a long-term commitment to manufacturing at the Glasgow factory.
The Scottish Trade Union Confederation GMB said that the company was silent about a possible investment in the Tollcross plant.
The factory employs over 500 workers who produce, among other products, Hobnob cookies and Rich Tea.
McVitie's owner, Pladis, said that over the past few years, it had invested more than £5 million in the whole area.
She added that employees and trade union representatives would be 'among the first to be informed' of any changes in the factory's operations.
In a letter to the construction company, GMB's Scottish unions expressed their concern that McVitie's will not deliver on its promises to finance and upgrade production lines.
GMB chief organiser Drew Duffy added: The fact that we have not received a clear response from the building manager on the company's needs and future investment plan at Tollcross is very worrying to our members.
Many generations of families have worked here and the staff come mostly from the local community and the Glasgow area, where working in the factory is a critical pillar of decent employment in an area of high unemployment and social exclusion.
In terms of jobs, wages and benefits - and despite the prospect of Brexit, rising living costs and declining slow manufacturing - the east end of Glasgow desperately needs a thriving manufacturer like McVitie's.
A spokesperson for Pladis said: The construction manager of Tollcross received a letter from GMB only yesterday and the company will issue a statement as soon as possible, as we appreciate the continued commitment to employees and trade union representatives.
A regular meeting with GMB's employees and representatives in Tollcross took place two months ago and many issues were openly discussed at this meeting.
We told our employees that, as with all companies operating in extremely competitive and uncertain economic conditions, we assess our operations on a regular basis, which applies to all our operations, so that we can continue to compete successfully with others.
She added: 'We have invested £5 million in the Tollcross area in recent years, mainly in production lines and efficiency.
We value the heritage of Tollcross and the local area very much and will inform employees and union representatives immediately of any changes in the operations of the local mill.
